    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The burning sensation during your HIIT sprints is a classic sign of metabolic stress, and it's often attributed to the buildup of hydrogen ions associated with lactic acid production. When you push yourself hard, your muscles need energy faster than oxygen can be supplied, which forces them into anaerobic respiration. To get rid of this metabolic byproduct, your body starts a process that involves the conversion of lactate into other substances, like glucose, primarily in the liver—a process called the Cori cycle. It's a complex chemical dance, but think of it like a very organized, albeit slightly chaotic, cleanup crew in your bloodstream.",
      "source": "target",
