    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, so it's basically just because of the oxygen thing. but why does it actually feel like a burn though? is it the acid itself or something else that's causing the actual sensation in the muscle tissue?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's not just the *lactic acid* itself that's causing the burn, though that's a big part of the story. The real culprit, in terms of the *sensation*, is the accumulation of hydrogen ions ($\\text{H}^+$) that accompany the lactate production. These excess ions lower the pH within your muscle cells, making the environment more acidic. This localized drop in pH interferes with the normal function of the muscle fibers, specifically affecting the enzymes and the contractile proteins, which is what your brain interprets as that intense, fiery burn.",
      "source": "target",
